I will be using the Riot Games API found at https://developer.riotgames.com/apis. Access is provided for noncommercial use through API keys that last for 24 hours before needing to be (freely) regenerated. Endpoints provide data regarding players and matches played across different game modes and games. My plan is to load League of Legends match data by looking up player IDs and obtain match history data for these players. There is an endpoint that provides IDs for all players for specific regions and tiers. Repeating the process across multiple players would create a small network of players and matches played. The nodes are players and a categorical variable available for each player per match is the teamPosition (TOP, JUNGLE, MIDDLE, BOTTOM, UTILITY). The teamPosition is the respective role of that player in that game. Edges are the connections between teammates from playing in a match together. Each team typically has one player in each position per match. Matches are zero sum between two teams; one team wins while the other loses. 

A hypothetical outcome that could be predicted from comparing degree centrality across categorical groups is the idea that teams with a higher degree centrality in the jungle position are more likely to win. For in-game metrics, I would also like to determine if certain actions such as fistBumpParticipation (how often a player will start or accept a fist bump after a good play) or onMyWayPing (alerting teammates that the player is heading to a location) lead to more wins. Do players with more connections in this network have higher ranks than other players? This can be determined by sorting players by eigenvector centrality and comparing this to the API's ranks for them.
